# CROSS-FOLIO CORRELATIONS

## ROTATION → ALTERNATING MOVEMENT NETWORK

Core folios: f.2r, 2v, 6v, 7v, 8v, 15r, 17r, 19v, 20r, 21r, 24r, 27r, 28r, 28v, 30r, 30v, 31r

Principle: Kurbel → Zahnradsegment → Pleuelstange → alternierende Bewegung

Applications: Sägewerk, Spinnrad, Tretmühle, Textilmaschinen

Free-wheel innovation (f.19v-21r) enables ONE-WAY conversion from alternating input

## CLOCK MECHANISM NETWORK

Primary folios: f.1r (tempo=escapement), f.4r (spring compensation), f.10v-11v (Chiaravalle), f.13v (striking), f.27v (24-hour)

Chiaravalle Abbey Clock: Dating anchor + technical model

Konzentrische Wellen: Hour/minute transmission via nested shafts (f.11r: 'poli in poli')

Mondphasen: Siderischer vs. Synodischer month calculations (f.10v-11r)

Schlossscheibe: 12-notch progressive striking control (f.12r, 13v, 27v, 81r)

## SPRING FORCE & COMPENSATION NETWORK

Compensation mechanisms: f.4r (spiral rack), f.13v (Stackfreed), f.14v, f.16r, f.45r, f.85r

Theory: f.4v (Blattfedern), f.11r (placement doctrine), f.51r, f.84v-85r (bending)

Maesstra calibration instrument: f.4v — Leonardo's self-designed experimental apparatus

Vite piramidata + corda = fusée equivalent (f.4r, f.85r)

## BEARING & FRICTION NETWORK

Anti-friction bearings: f.12v (Giulio witness), f.20v (ball-globoid), f.26r (ball vs. roller)

Theory corpus: Part 2 f.88v-91v (103r-100r) — comprehensive friction studies

Wear analysis: f.3r (mills), f.13r (systematic), f.20r (gear ratios), Part 2 f.91v

Reti 1971: Leonardo introduced friction ratio concept F/W

# IDENTIFIED DISCREPANCIES

## GERMAN TRANSLATION vs. ITALIAN SOURCE

f.3r Absatz 5 conclusion

ITALIAN: 'mai potrà altro fare' = 'can never do otherwise'

GERMAN 1974: 'nie so drehen' (incorrect)

CORRECTION: 'nie anders drehen' — gears with non-integer ratios wear evenly

f.4v Blattfeder text incompleteness

Maschat 1989 notes missing portions in German edition re: spring force analysis

## SCHOLARLY INTERPRETATION DISPUTES

f.10v Chiaravalle moon mechanism

Simoni 1975: Called Leonardo's drawings 'forgery' — REFUTED by Hall/Bates 1976

f.4r Spring compensation mechanism

Bedini/Reti 1974: 'Not functioning mechanism'

Klemm 1979: Defends functionality; cites Paulus Alemanus (Rome ~1480)

f.3r Miller gear ratios

Maschat 1989: Misread as 'Leonardo holds opposite (wrong) view'

Correct reading: Leonardo distinguishes TWO gear types (data vs. load)

# WITNESS & DATING EVIDENCE

## NAMED WITNESSES

GIULIO (German collaborator)

f.12v: 'Dice Giulio aver visto nella Magni[a]...' — bearing technology testimony

Entered service: 18 March 1493 (Ms. Paris H f.105r, 106v)

Also mentioned: Ms. Paris H (1493-1494), Codex Forster III f.88v

Significance: German mill technology transfer to Leonardo

GUGLIELMO DELLA VOLPAIA

Florentine clockmaker — Leonardo's contact pre-Milan

Pedretti 1957, 1978; Taglialagamba 2010 establish connection

## CHRONOLOGICAL ANCHORS

1 January 1493 (f.1r) — EXPLICIT DATE establishes codex timeline

18 March 1493 — Giulio enters service (cross-codex confirmation)

Chiaravalle Abbey Clock — Technical model for astronomical mechanisms (f.10v-11v)

Codex Atlanticus f.205r (~1506-08) — Parallel to f.1r flame/water note (Pedretti)

Ms. Paris B f.20r, 53v, 54r (1488-89) — Sector-rope precedents (Beck, Reti)

Codex Forster I.2 f.46r (1487-90) — Free-wheel precursor sketch (Reti)

# CRITICAL TERMINOLOGY INDEX

**● Tempo**

Escapement (Hemmung) — NOT 'time' in clock context (f.1r, 5v, 8r, 9v, 27c, 48v)

**● Carello / Caregli**

Ritzel (smaller gear/pinion) — rare usage, documented by Manni/Biffi (f.1r)

**● Maesstra**

Master instrument / calibration device — Leonardo's term (f.4v, 91v, Atlanticus 878v)

**● Drehling**

Triebstockrad (lantern pinion) — preferred over 'Stockgetriebe' (Tivig critique)

**● Rocca**

Drehling OR roller (context-dependent); Brunelleschi usage = crane roller (Reti 1964)

**● Subbio**

Roller/cylinder (transport), Weberbaum, Walzwerk (f.2v); later: winding beam

**● Curro**

Transport roller (cilindro per trasportare cose pesanti) — f.2v

**● Confregazione**

Reibung (friction) — systematic studies throughout

**● Consumamento**

Verschleiß (wear/abrasion) — distinct from friction (f.13r, Part 2 f.91v)

**● Vite perpetua**

Endless screw (Endlosschnecke) — NOT perpetual motion (f.19r)

**● Vite piramidata**

Konische Schraube (fusée cone) — spring force compensation (f.4r, 85r)

**● Inpeto / Impetus**

Schwung (momentum/kinetic energy) — f.21r: 'accrescimento di velocità'

**● Fuga**

Flucht/Schwung (centrifugal tendency) — f.21r: kinetic overshoot

**● Molla**

Feder (spring) — Blattfeder, Schraubenfeder, Spiralfeder

**● Tenperato**

Gehärtet (hardened steel) — critical material specification (f.12v, 13v)

# BNE THEMATIC CROSS-REFERENCE

The Spanish BNE catalogue organizes Madrid I by **THEME**, not sequential order. This section maps thematic categories to analyzed folios.

## PRIORITY CATEGORIES FOR ANALYSIS

### ★ RELOJES (CLOCKS) — PRIMARY TARGET

Analyzed: f.1r (tempo), f.4r (compensation), f.10v-11v (Chiaravalle), f.13v (striking)

Pending: f.27v (24-hour), f.32r-C (wind escapement), numerous Part 2 folios

Priority claim: Complete verge-and-foliot escapement specification predating Huygens 150+ years

### ★ PRINCIPIOS DE MECÁNICA (MECHANICAL PRINCIPLES) — THEORETICAL FOUNDATION

Fricción-resistencia-desgaste: f.12v-13r (Giulio witness), Part 2 f.88v-91v

Fuerza: f.4v (Maesstra), f.5r (gear contact), Part 2 f.51r (spring theory)

Gravedad-peso: f.4r distinction, Part 2 extensive treatment

Movimiento-percusión: f.21r (impetus), Part 2 f.60v ('accrescimento di velocità')

Rotación: f.2r-31r (conversion network), f.19v-21r (free-wheel)

Velocidad-aceleración: f.21r (millstone), Part 2 Bradwardine/Blasius framework

### ★ ASTRONOMÍA Y CONCEPCIÓN DEL TIEMPO (ASTRONOMY/TIME) — ORRERY CALCULATIONS

f.10v-11r: Mondphasen with siderischer/synodischer month calculations

Planetary gear ratios: Astronomically coherent (white paper confirms)

Combined clock-and-orrery modular platform evidence

